04394nam a22005775i 9780822397571DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20132013ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223975717 a10.1515/97808223975712doi  a(DE-B1597)554413  a(OCoLC)840897776  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aJV6217 7aSOC0070002bisacsh04a304.800aHow Immigrants Impact Their Homelands /cSusan Eva Eckstein, Susan Eva Eckstein, Adil Najam. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (277 p.) :b6 tables, 11 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 ae-Duke books scholarly collection00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tFIGURES AND TABLES -- tPREFACE -- t1 Immigrants from Developing Countries -- t2 Migration and Development -- t3 How Overseas Chinese Spurred the Economic ''Miracle'' in Their Homeland -- t4 Immigrants' Globalization of the Indian Economy -- t5 How Cuban Americans Are -- t6 Immigrant Impacts in Mexico -- t7 ''Turks Abroad'' Redefine Turkish Nationalism -- t8 Moroccan Migrants as Unlikely Captains of Industry -- t9 The Gender Revolution in the Philippines -- t10 Beyond Social Remittances -- t11 Economic Uncertainties, Social Strains, and HIV Risks -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow Immigrants Impact Their Homelands examines the range of economic, social, and cultural impacts immigrants have had, both knowingly and unknowingly, in their home countries. The book opens with overviews of the ways migrants become agents of homeland development. The essays that follow focus on the varied impacts immigrants have had in China, India, Cuba, Mexico, the Philippines, Mozambique, and Turkey. One contributor examines the role Indians who worked in Silicon Valley played in shaping the structure, successes, and continued evolution of India's IT industry. Another traces how Salvadoran immigrants extend U.S. gangs and their brutal violence to El Salvador and neighboring countries. The tragic situation in Mozambique of economically desperate émigrés who travel to South Africa to work, contract HIV while there, and infect their wives upon their return is the subject of another essay. Taken together, the essays show the multiple ways countries are affected by immigration. Understanding these effects will provide a foundation for future policy reforms in ways that will strengthen the positive and minimize the negative effects of the current mobile world.Contributors. Victor Agadjanian, Boaventura Cau, José Miguel Cruz, Susan Eva Eckstein, Kyle Eischen, David Scott FitzGerald, Natasha Iskander, Riva Kastoryano, Cecilia Menjívar, Adil Najam, Rhacel Salazar Parreñas, Alejandro Portes, Min Ye  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aEmigration and immigrationxEconomic aspects. 0aEmigration and immigrationxPolitical aspects. 0aEmigration and immigrationxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh1 aEckstein, Susan Eva, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNajam, Adil, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822397571zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822397571423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822397571.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles